**There is no top-level `CMakeLists.txt`.** Deps and Sneeze are two fully independent CMake projects. The scripts in `scripts/` are the only glue: they invoke `cmake -S deps` for dependencies and `cmake -S src` for Sneeze, with no shared outer project.

Sneeze is a static library. Artemis owns `main.cpp`, SDL3 windowing (`canvas/Canvas`), and all browser chrome. Sneeze owns everything else: scene management, rendering, the camera orbit controller (`VIEWPORT::VIEW`), and test data injection (`astro/`). Artemis's role is limited to taking pixels from Sneeze and presenting them, and feeding raw input to Sneeze.

Artemis is a separate repository with its own `project.mdc`. See the Artemis repository for application-level details (installer, updater, chrome, SDL3 windowing).

## Architecture Reference

The OMB architecture is fully documented in `OMB_Architecture_4.md` (the authoritative architecture document, version 4, 2026 Q2, maintained outside this repo). This document covers the MBE (Metaverse Browser Engine), its core abstractions, the SOM, rendering engine, UI toolkit, identity, avatars, spatial audio, and the content provider ecosystem.

### MBE Core Abstractions

The MBE relies on six industry-adopted open standards that abstract the underlying hardware. These are genuinely different kinds of things — APIs, bytecode formats, and a programming model — which is why they are called "core abstractions" rather than "runtime interfaces."

- **ANARI** — rendering abstraction (scene description, not GPU calls). High-level scene graph API where the browser describes *what* to render and the ANARI device decides *how*. Extremely thin — imposes no measurable overhead.
- **SPIR-V Compute via Vox** — browser-internal GPU compute. Parallel workloads (physics, spatial audio, proximity, coordinate transforms, IK) are authored as GLSL compute shaders, compiled to SPIR-V at build time, and dispatched through **Vox** at runtime. Vox is a standalone library (`MetaversalCorp/Vox`) that abstracts Vulkan, DX12, and Metal compute dispatch behind a polymorphic C++ API. The browser writes one SPIR-V shader; Vox handles cross-compilation (SPIRV-Cross) and GPU-specific pipeline setup. ANARI does not and will not support compute shaders — Vox replaces the original ANARI compute path. Not visible to services — it's the browser team's internal compute tool.
- **SPIR-V** — GPU interchange format for both graphics shaders and compute shaders. Content providers ship SPIR-V bytecode; the browser validates it (SPIRV-Tools) and passes it to ANARI, which handles backend translation internally.
- **OpenXR** — device I/O abstraction for VR/AR headsets, controllers, hand tracking, eye tracking. Confirmed indispensable — no realistic alternative exists.
- **WASM** — sandboxed execution for third-party service logic. Each connected service runs WASM modules with isolated memory, CPU budgets, and controlled host access. A misbehaving module cannot crash the browser, read other services' data, or access the filesystem.
- **SMAP** (Service Model Access Protocol) — fabric connectivity and service driver layer. Abstracts the network so the browser can connect to any spatial fabric without knowledge of its underlying protocol.

### Core Concepts
- **Spatial Fabric** — a collection of services that together define a spatial environment
- **Service** — a discrete unit of functionality within a spatial fabric
- **SOM** (Scene Object Model) — the browser's internal scene graph (like the DOM for 3D)
- **Proximity** — the primary discovery and connection mechanism, replacing URLs

## Sneeze Codebase

### Project Layout

All paths are relative to the repository root (`Sneeze/`):

- **Source code:** `src/`
- **Test code:** `tests/`
- **Sneeze build output:** `builds/<platform>/` — single multi-config tree. `build/` is the CMake scratch (one directory carries both Debug and Release); `install/<config>/lib/` holds `Sneeze.lib`/`libSneeze.a`; `install/<config>/bin/` holds test executables and CLI tools. The `install/<config>/` wrapper mirrors each dep's `libs/<Name>/install/{bin,lib}` layout for full symmetry (gitignored). Use the Visual Studio generator on Windows and the Ninja Multi-Config generator on Linux/macOS so one `cmake -S src -B builds/<platform>/build` call covers both configs and `cmake --build … --config <config>` selects at build time.
- **Dependency source clones:** `deps/repos/<Name>/` — one shared clone per dep, reused across configs (gitignored)
- **Dependency build/install trees:** `deps/builds/<platform>/<config>/libs/<Name>/` — each has `build/` (scratch) and `install/` (usable artifacts) (gitignored)
- **Two isolated CMake trees, no top-level bridge:**
  - `deps/CMakeLists.txt` — standalone deps project. Knows only about `deps/`. Invoked as `cmake -S deps`. All-deps mode by default; `-DDEP=<name>` for single-dep CI builds. Iterates `deps/*.cmake` and declares `add_dependencies(...)` ordering.
  - `src/CMakeLists.txt` — standalone Sneeze project. Knows only about `src/` and `tests/`. Invoked as `cmake -S src`. Finds deps in `${LIBS_DIR}/<Name>/install/`, forces output into `${SNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT}/install/$<LOWER_CASE:$<CONFIG>>/{lib,bin}` via generator expressions on the output-directory variables — Debug and Release land in separate `install/{debug,release}/` siblings emitted from a single multi-config build tree (symmetric with each dep's per-config `install/{bin,lib}` layout).
  - **Neither CMakeLists ever references the other branch.** The scripts are the only glue.
- **Per-dep CMake files:** `deps/*.cmake` — single source of truth. One `ExternalProject_Add` per dep; included by `deps/CMakeLists.txt` and unchanged for CI's single-dep path.
- **Test build:** `tests/CMakeLists.txt` (defines all test executables; pulled in by `src/CMakeLists.txt`)
- **Platform slugs:** `windows-x64`, `linux-x64`, `linux-arm64`, `macos-arm64`, `macos-x64`, `ios-arm64`, `android-arm64` — must match `Artemis/pkg/manifest.json`.
- **Config:** `Debug` or `Release` (lowercased in paths: `debug`/`release`).

### Module Structure

All C++ code lives in namespace `SNEEZE` with sub-namespaces per module (e.g. `SNEEZE::persona`, `SNEEZE::renderer`). The `astro` namespace (`SNEEZE::astro`) remains for the stateless injection function only; `CELESTIAL` and `ORBIT` now live in the root `SNEEZE` namespace under `context/scene/`. Public API headers live in `include/`; private implementation headers live under `src/`. Source files are under `src/`:

| Module | Namespace | Purpose | Phase |
|--------|-----------|---------|-------|
| `sneeze/` | `SNEEZE` | Engine-level shared code: foundational types (Vec3, Quat), engine lifecycle (ENGINE class with pimpl), and the THREAD base class (managed thread lifecycle). ENGINE is the single entry point -- owns all module init/shutdown, viewport management, and path management. Delegates agent lifecycle and the engine thread to CONTROL. Per-viewport resources (renderer, input, framebuffer) are owned by VIEWPORT instances. SCENE is owned by CONTEXT. Public header: `include/Sneeze.h`. Implementation: `sneeze/Engine.cpp`, `sneeze/Thread.cpp`. Also: `Engine.h` (THREAD declaration), `Types.h`, `Sneeze.md`. | PoC |
| `sneeze/control/` | `SNEEZE` | Engine thread, agent pools, metronome, and job queues. CONTROL (engine thread, metronome, inherits THREAD) owns a vector of POOLs. POOL is the non-template base (agents + Hz-driven tick). POOL_QUEUE<JOB_PTR> adds a typed job queue with Post/Grab. POOL_CYCLE is a perpetual job pool for compositor jobs (jobs remain in pool until explicitly Remove()'d, Grab() routes Create/Destroy to agent 0 for Filament thread affinity, Ready jobs round-robin by longest-ago-rendered via `m_nLastFrame`). AGENT base (inherits THREAD, Main() pure virtual) + AGENT::COMPOSITOR (queue-driven via POOL_CYCLE, 1 agent) + AGENT::SCRUB (queue-driven, 2 agents) + AGENT::FETCH (queue-driven, 16 agents, HTTP downloads) + AGENT::C (signal-driven, 30 Hz placeholder). Job classes: IJOB (base, Cancel/Release), JOB_FETCH (fetch jobs, inherits IJOB), JOB_SCRUB (scrub jobs, inherits IJOB), JOB_COMPOSITOR (perpetual viewport rendering job, inherits IJOB). `FETCH_RESULT` is a plain struct in the `SNEEZE` namespace (declared in `Control.h`), used by both the control layer and NETWORK — there is no separate `NETWORK::FETCH_RESULT`. JOB_FETCH carries a `bool m_bFetch` flag (set via constructor) that distinguishes real fetch jobs from notify-only jobs (asynchronous notifications for cached/failed files). JOB_COMPOSITOR owns a state machine (kSTATE_CREATE -> kSTATE_RENDER -> kSTATE_PRESENT -> kSTATE_DESTROY), per-job mutex (`m_mxJob`), and a cancellation handshake (`m_mxCancel` recursive_mutex + `m_cvCancel` condition_variable_any + `m_bCancelled` flag). `Cancel()` sets state to kSTATE_DESTROY and blocks until `Complete()` signals `m_cvCancel`. Single header `Control.h` declares all. Files: `Control.cpp`, `Pool.cpp`, `Pool_Queue.cpp`, `Pool_Cycle.cpp`, `Agent.cpp`, `Compositor.cpp`, `Scrub.cpp`, `Fetch.cpp`, `AgentC.cpp`, `IJob.cpp`. See `Control.md` for full documentation. | Active |
| `astro/` | `astro` | **Superseded by WASM solar system module.** Stateless solar system test data injection. Contains `InjectSolarSystem(FABRIC*)` (free function in `BodyData.cpp`) and `RMCOBJECT` (local-only body data, no static globals). `CELESTIAL` and `ORBIT` (pure math) remain in `context/scene/` (`SNEEZE` namespace) — they are permanent scene-module classes, not astro. The `astro/` code itself (`BodyData.cpp`, `RMCObject.cpp/.h`, `UVSphere.cpp/.h`) is no longer called at runtime — `InjectSolarSystem` is commented out and the WASM module now populates the scene. Pending removal once the WASM pipeline is fully validated. | PoC |
| `viewport/renderer/` | `renderer` | Abstract rendering interface + ANARI implementation (device chosen by caller — Halogen in production) | PoC |
| `viewport/view/` | `view` | Camera orbit controller (now `VIEWPORT::VIEW` struct with `Update()` method, decoupled from windowing -- takes raw input deltas). One instance per viewport, updated by the compositor. | PoC |
| `context/scene/` | `SNEEZE` | Scene Object Model -- the browser's internal scene graph. All scene classes (SCENE, FABRIC, FABRIC_ROOT, NODE) are peers in the `SNEEZE` namespace, declared in `include/Scene.h`. SCENE (root container, owned by CONTEXT, `Context()` accessor, owns FABRIC_ROOT). FABRIC (spatial fabric branch, constructor takes `SCENE*` + `NODE*` attach point + `FABRIC*` parent, `Scene()` accessor, pImpl pattern — Impl delegates MSF loading to file-local `MSF_FETCH` class implementing `SNEEZE::IFILE`, owns `MSF*` + `SNEEZE::FILE*` + `CONTAINER*`, URL identity, container pointer). FABRIC_ROOT (derived from FABRIC, structural root, creates primary attachment node + root container with synthetic CID). NODE (structural graph element, constructor takes `FABRIC*` + `NODE*` parent, pImpl pattern -- Impl holds all internal members and inherits `SNEEZE::IFILE` for automatic texture loading). Two-step construction: constructor links into tree, `Initialize(MAP_OBJECT*)` assigns the 3D payload and triggers texture fetch if the map object has a texture URL. Also contains: EPOCH (Julian date calculations, time propagation), ORBIT (Keplerian orbital elements and position computation, embedded by value in MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL), and CELESTIAL (static utility functions for ecliptic/equatorial frame conversion and pole orientation). Owner/parent pointers are constructor invariants -- no setters, getters drop "Get" (e.g. `Fabric()` not `GetFabric()`). Method naming: Type_Verb_Qualifier pattern (e.g. `Node_Add()`, `Node_Remove()`). Includes AccessControl (read/write enforcement for WASM host functions), Events (watch registration + callback dispatch on add/remove/modify), and SpatialIndex (BVH with frustum culling and proximity queries). MAP_OBJECT base class + derived types (Root, Celestial, Terrestrial, Physical) carry all 3D properties. Public header: `include/Scene.h` (declares SCENE, FABRIC, FABRIC_ROOT, NODE). Private headers deleted -- `Node.h` and `Fabric.h` no longer exist; all declarations live in the public header. Files: `Scene.cpp`, `Fabric.cpp`, `Node.cpp`, `MapObject.h`, `Orbit.h`/`Orbit.cpp`, `Celestial.h`/`Celestial.cpp`, `Epoch.h`/`Epoch.cpp`, `AccessControl.h`/`AccessControl.cpp`, `Events.h`/`Events.cpp`, `SpatialIndex.h`/`SpatialIndex.cpp`. | Active |
| `context/network/` | `SNEEZE` | Network resource system with file caching. NETWORK (per-context, constructor takes `CONTEXT*`) owns ASSET objects (one per URL, evicted from memory when last FILE closes). Public types (eASSET_STATE, eASSET_EXT, FILE, IFILE, IENUM_FILE) are peers in the `SNEEZE` namespace (un-nested from NETWORK to allow forward declaration across module boundaries). ASSET, RULE, and REQUEST remain private. `SNEEZE::FILE` conflicts with C's `::FILE` in translation units that use `using namespace SNEEZE;` at file scope — qualify as `SNEEZE::FILE` where ambiguous (done in `File.cpp`, `Asset.cpp`, `Network.cpp`, `Fabric.cpp`, `NetworkTest.cpp`). `FETCH_RESULT` is a plain struct in the `SNEEZE` namespace (declared in `Control.h`), shared by the control layer and NETWORK — there is no separate `NETWORK::FETCH_RESULT`. Fetches are dispatched as JOB_FETCH jobs through CONTROL's pooled AGENT::FETCH workers (16 threads). ASSET stores `IJOB* m_pAsset_Fetch` (cancelled on re-fetch or destruction). A file-local `ASSET_FETCH` class in `Asset.cpp` (derives from `JOB_FETCH`) bridges fetch completion to `ASSET::FetchComplete`. Two constructors: (1) real fetch (`IsFetch() == true`) with URL/paths/hash, and (2) notify-only (`IsFetch() == false`) with FILE*/STATE for asynchronous cached/failed notifications. All FILE notifications (OnFileReady/OnFileFailed) are asynchronous — even for already-cached files, the notification is posted as a notify-only job to the fetch pool, preventing re-entrancy bugs during File_Open/Initialize. `ASSET::Resolve()` and `ASSET::Fail()` have been inlined into `FetchComplete` (single-caller methods eliminated). Routing: `NETWORK::Queue_Post_Fetch(JOB_FETCH*)` -> `ENGINE::Queue_Post_Fetch` -> `ENGINE::Impl::Queue_Post_Fetch` -> `CONTROL::Queue_Post_Fetch`. `FetchComplete` releases the fetch's implicit counts via `Detach(nullptr)` + `m_pNetwork->Asset_Close(nullptr, this)` — routing through proper lifecycle methods so `Meta_Save`/`Meta_Reset`/`Evict` trigger when counts reach zero. `Close(nullptr)` skips the file-list erase (designed for this case). `Asset_Close` uses `pAsset->Pathname()` unconditionally for the map key. Callers open files via `File_Open()` (always returns `FILE*`) and return them via `File_Close()`. Three usage cases: (1) active fetch with listener (implicit Attach/Detach), (2) inspector observation (explicit Attach/Detach, no fetch), (3) passive open without listener (no implicit attach). FILE stores `VIEWPORT*` for inspector notification routing and `CID` by value for container identity. All files persist on disk across restarts; files with an SRI hash are additionally integrity-verified. Sidecar `.meta` files per ASSET saved on eviction and shutdown. `rules.json` stores staleness rules and the `nNextMetaIx` counter. Path generation via `eASSET_EXT` enum (kASSET_EXT_DATA/kASSET_EXT_TEMP/kASSET_EXT_META) and `Path(eType)`. All files stored on disk with per-CID fan-out directories under the viewport's permanent path + "/Network". FILE snapshot fields split into three phases: SnapshotInitial (URL, nAssetIx -- set once at construction), SnapshotProgress (state, queued/start times -- during fetch), SnapshotFinal (all settled fields -- when fetch resolves). Copies of ASSET display data -- getters read from snapshot, not ASSET. `nFileIx` (monotonic FILE handle index) and `nAssetIx` (monotonic ASSET content-version index, persisted). ASSET lifecycle: two counters `m_nCount_Open` (structural, how many FILEs reference this ASSET) and `m_nCount_Attach` (active listeners, triggers fetch). `Meta_Load` on first attach, `Meta_Save`/`Meta_Reset` on last detach. ASSET pImpl with `m_mxAsset` (recursive_mutex). FILE pImpl with `m_mxFile` (std::mutex). FILE dual-flag deletion model: `m_bPending_Close` (caller is done) and `m_bPending_Clear` (inspector has cleared) — FILE is deleted from `m_apFile` only when both are true. `SetPending_Close`/`SetPending_Clear` return bool (true when value changes, prevents double-close/double-clear). Delete-before-erase order in all removal paths. FILE::Close() does not degrade the FILE — inspector retains full access (Attach, ReadData, Headers, etc.) until it also clears. `FILE::Asset()` accessor removed (ASSET not exposed externally). `FILE::IsAttached()` removed. Hash verification consolidated into ASSET::Impl. Staleness rules in `rules.json` checked on attach for READY assets. Network inspector data layer: high-res timing (queued/start/end), HTTP status, sequence numbers, history list, served-from-cache detection, container identity, OnNetworkFileCreated/Changed/Deleted notifications broadcast to IVIEWPORT hosts. File_Enum(IENUM*, VIEWPORT*) walks files for inspection. First real consumer: NODE textures fetched automatically via `MapObject_Set()`. Public header: `include/Network.h`. Implementation: `Asset.cpp`, `File.cpp`, `Network.cpp`. See `Network.md` for full documentation. **Build status: compiles clean, all network tests pass (69 assertions across 23 test groups).** FILE now owns all path computation (m_sPath_Permanent, m_sDiskKey, sPath/sFilename/sPathname). ASSET map keyed by pathname (not URL). Close() calls Detach() immediately. Fetch timing via NETWORK::SecondsSinceEpoch(). File_Open with null listener returns null for uncached URLs. curl_global_init/cleanup moved from NETWORK to ENGINE. | Active |
| `context/console/` | `SNEEZE` | Per-context developer console, analogous to a web browser's console object. CONSOLE (per-context, constructor takes `CONTEXT*`) owns a global ring buffer (`m_apEntry`, capped `deque<shared_ptr<const ENTRY>>`) and a stream map (`m_umpStream`, `unordered_map<const CID*, STREAM*>`, one per CID, enforced single-stream-per-CID). Two-tier storage: (1) global ring buffer for all entries across all containers (in-memory, capped at `m_nEntries_Cache`, default 16384), (2) per-container disk-backed STREAMs writing JSONL block files in a rolling window. All public types (eENTRY_LEVEL, ENTRY, STREAM, IENUM_ENTRY, IENUM_STREAM) are peers in the `SNEEZE` namespace (un-nested from CONSOLE to allow forward declaration across module boundaries). BLOCK is private (declared in the internal `Console.h`). ENTRY is immutable, shared via `shared_ptr<const ENTRY>`, self-stamps with `system_clock::now()` in the constructor. STREAM (symmetric with SILO) groups BLOCKs for a single container, owns logging methods (Log/Debug/Info/Warn/Error/Assert), grouping (Group/GroupCollapsed/GroupEnd with `m_nGroupDepth`), counting (`m_umpCount`), and timing (`m_umpTime` using `steady_clock`). BLOCKs are owned directly by STREAM (not shared via CONSOLE). BLOCK (symmetric with STORAGE::UNIT) wraps a single JSONL `.log` file on disk, lazy-loaded entry cache, lazy-opened ofstream for writes. STREAM manages block rotation: when a block fills (`m_nEntries_Block`, default 4096), `Rotate()` creates a new block and deletes the oldest if the rolling window exceeds `m_nBlocks` (default 4). Blocks are created lazily — a new stream starts with `m_nBlock == -1` and no blocks; the first entry triggers creation of block #0000. Meta sidecar per-STREAM (not per-BLOCK) records `block` and `blockEntryCount`, read on Initialize via `Meta_Load()`, written on Detach via `Meta_Save()`. CID sourcing: `Console::Impl::Stream_Open` receives `const CID*` from CONTAINER::Identity(); returns `nullptr` if a stream for that CID already exists. Entry creation: STREAM calls `Console::Entry_Create()` which timestamps, sequences, ring-buffers the entry, and fires `OnConsoleEntryCreated`/`OnConsoleEntryDeleted` ICONTEXT callbacks. Disk layout: `<TemporaryPath>/Console/<persona>/<fp-2>/<fp-22>/<container>-NNNN.log`. Entry serialization: `ToJson()` writes epoch seconds as `"stamp"` (double), `FromJson()` reconstitutes `system_clock::time_point`. `FormatStamp()` produces `HH:MM:SS.mmm`. `MessageParts()` parses JSON arrays for structured display. Notifications: `OnConsoleStreamCreated/Deleted`, `OnConsoleEntryCreated/Deleted` via ICONTEXT. Thread safety: `m_mxConsole` (recursive_mutex) on CONSOLE, `m_mxStream` (recursive_mutex) per STREAM, `m_mutex` (recursive_mutex) per BLOCK. Public header: `include/Console.h`. Private header: `Console.h` (declares `ICONSOLE_IMPL` and `BLOCK`). Implementation: `Console.cpp`, `Stream.cpp`, `Block.cpp`, `Entry.cpp`. See `Console.md` for full documentation. **Build status: compiles and links clean, 44/44 console tests pass. ~90% complete.** Not yet implemented: WASM host function wiring, null-CID engine stream, inspector UI, stream-level entry aggregation, block rotation on config change. | Active |
