| `THREAD` | `sneeze` | Base class for managed thread lifecycle. Declared in `sneeze/Engine.h`, implemented in `sneeze/Thread.cpp`. Encapsulates all threading primitives: `std::thread*`, `std::mutex`, `std::condition_variable`, shutdown flag, ready handshake. Mutex and condition variable are `private`. `Wait(std::function<bool()>)` acquires the mutex and calls `m_cvThread.wait(lock, fnWork)` — `fnWork` is the condition-variable predicate (`std::function<bool()>`); it returns **true** when the wait should end (same contract as `std::condition_variable::wait`). **`Wait(std::chrono::milliseconds)`** calls `m_cvThread.wait_for` for up to that duration or until `Signal` wakes the thread. **Invariant:** neither `Wait` overload’s implementation reads `m_bShutdown` or calls `IsShutdown()` — those two bodies are cv + mutex primitives only; shutdown and other policy belong in derived `Main()` implementations and in predicate callables passed to the predicate `Wait`. `Signal(bool)` (`false` = wake only, e.g. cleanup queue; `true` = latch shutdown and wake). `Initialize()` spawns the thread (calls pure virtual `Main()`), blocks until the thread calls `Ready()`, returns `m_bResult_Initialize`. **`Join()`** (protected) — calls `Signal(true)`, then `if (m_pthThread->joinable()) m_pthThread->join()`. Pure synchronization, no allocation/deallocation. `~THREAD()` calls `Join()` then `delete m_pthThread; m_pthThread = nullptr;` (symmetric with constructor's `new`). `joinable()` makes `Join()` safe to call multiple times. **Critical rule: every derived class whose `Main()` accesses derived-class members must call `Join()` in its own destructor.** C++ destructor ordering destroys derived members before the base destructor runs, so `~THREAD()`'s join would be too late — `Main()` would be accessing destroyed members. `~THREAD()` calls `Join()` as a last-resort safety net but the derived destructor is the correct place. All current THREAD-derived classes (`CONTROL`, `AGENT`, `COMPOSITOR`, `SCRUB`, `FETCH`, `C`) call `Join()` in their destructors. `Ready(bool bResult = true)` signals the initializing thread that startup is complete. `IsShutdown()` returns the shutdown flag. Non-copyable, non-movable. See **THREAD / CONTROL / AGENT wait and shutdown contract** under Design Principles. |
| `CONTROL` | `sneeze/control` | Owns the engine thread, pool lifecycle, metronome, and job queues. Inherits `THREAD`. Constructor takes `ENGINE* pEngine`. `Initialize(int& nAgentCount)` calls `THREAD::Initialize()` which spawns the engine thread (`Main()`); populates `nAgentCount` on return. `~CONTROL()` calls `Join()` before member destruction (see THREAD `Join()` rule). `Main()` is the control thread's lifecycle: creates pools from a static `AGENT_INIT` factory table (each entry has `fnCreate_Pool` and `fnCreate_Agent`), runs the drift-free metronome (`Wait(1ms)` loop, fixed-origin scheduling, `timeBeginPeriod(1)` on Windows), ticks pools with `nHertz > 0`, and on exit deletes all pools (`~POOL` tears down agents). **Metronome loop structure:** `if (!IsShutdown()) { …tick pools… } else break;` then `Wait(1ms)`. Public API: `Queue_Post_Fetch(JOB_FETCH*)` -> `Pool_Fetch().Post()`, `Queue_Post_Scrub(JOB_SCRUB*)` -> `Pool_Scrub().Post()`, `Queue_Post_Compositor(JOB_COMPOSITOR*)` -> `Pool_Compositor().Post()`. `Engine()` returns `m_pEngine`. Members: `m_pEngine`, `m_apPool` (vector<POOL*>). Pool config: COMPOSITOR (2 agents, 0 Hz, queue-driven via POOL_CYCLE), SCRUB (2 agents, 0 Hz, queue-driven), FETCH (16 agents, 0 Hz, queue-driven), C (1 agent, 30 Hz). See `Control.md` for full documentation. File: `Control.cpp`. The old cleanup relay mechanism (`Cleanup_Queue`/`Cleanup_SwapQueue`/`m_bCleanupPending` on CONTROL) has been eliminated — `ENGINE::Impl::Scrub()` now directly creates `JOB_SCRUB` and posts it via `CONTROL::Queue_Post_Scrub()`. The metronome loop is simplified to just tick pools and call `Diagnostics()`. `Engine()` accessor returns `m_pEngine`. Synchronization: inherited `THREAD` primitives via `Wait` / `Signal` (metronome timing). Defined first in `Control.h` (before AGENT) with `class AGENT;` forward declaration. File: `Control.cpp`.  |
