## Proof of Concept — Solar System (COMPLETE)

Phase 1 ported the existing Solar System simulation (`E:\Dev\SolarSystem\`) from JavaScript/Three.js to C++/ANARI as a disposable proof of concept. The solar system exercises the ANARI rendering pipeline end-to-end (multiple objects, real-time updates, camera controls) while establishing the module structure, build system, and coding conventions that the full browser will use. **The solar system now runs entirely via the WASM pipeline** — a Rust WASM module (`tests/wasm/solar_system/`) populates the SOM via Scene host functions, replacing the C++ `astro::InjectSolarSystem()` injection path (which is commented out and pending removal). `CELESTIAL` and `ORBIT` (orbital math classes) live in `context/scene/` in the SNEEZE namespace as permanent scene-module types used by `MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL`. The compositor agent (`AGENT::COMPOSITOR`) drives all rendering using hierarchical `WORLD_FRAME` traversal — it is entirely oblivious to orbital mechanics, tilt, spin, and precession, consuming only the virtual `Position()` and `Rotation()` methods on `MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL`. Artemis's `main.cpp` has been reduced to window management, input forwarding, and framebuffer presentation.

### What Phase 1 Delivered
- Native C++ executable rendering the solar system via ANARI (originally helide CPU ray tracer; cut over to Halogen PBR once it landed)
- Orbital mechanics as browser-level C++ computation (Kepler solver, precession, frame conversions)
- Embedded planet/star/moon data for the full solar system (Sun + 9 planet systems + bodies)
- Abstract RENDERER interface with concrete ANARI_RENDERER implementation (device chosen by caller)
- Camera orbit controller decoupled from windowing (raw input deltas)
- Module structure ready for the full browser
- **Engine-driven rendering pipeline:** ENGINE class owns all module initialization and the `AGENT::COMPOSITOR` (queue-driven via `POOL_CYCLE`). Scene data is now populated by the WASM solar system module (fetched via MSF pipeline) — `astro::InjectSolarSystem` is commented out. Artemis reduced to: create window -> create `ENGINE` -> call `Initialize()` -> `Context_Open(pHost, sUrl)` -> main loop (poll events, feed input via viewport, present framebuffer) -> `Context_Close()` -> `Shutdown()`. Frame-ready notification via `IVIEWPORT::OnFrameReady()` callback (per viewport). Shared double-buffered RGBA framebuffer with mutex protection per viewport. Console window attached via `AllocConsole()` for Win32 GUI app debug output.

### Known Phase 1 Limitations
- No HUD or on-screen labels
- No animation speed controls in the UI (code supports +/- keys but no visual feedback)
- Sphere bodies have no texture mapping yet — needs material/texture support wired through Halogen's PBR pipeline
- These are Phase 2 refinements on a working foundation

### Engine-Driven Rendering Pipeline

**Sneeze owns all 3D object rendering, scene management, and the rendering loop. Artemis's role is limited to taking pixels from Sneeze and displaying them, and feeding raw input to Sneeze.**

**Key architectural decisions:**

- **ENGINE as single entry point.** `ENGINE::Initialize()` is parameterless -- reads configuration from the `IENGINE*` host. Initializes all engine modules (wasm, spirv, xr, ui), then starts the engine metronome thread (which creates and initializes all agents). Per-context resources (console, network, storage, scene, viewport/renderer) are created by `Context_Open()`. `ENGINE::Shutdown()` closes all contexts, stops the engine thread, then tears down subsystems in reverse order.
- **Nested initialization / reverse-order shutdown.** Each module init nests inside the prior success. On failure, only the successfully-initialized modules are shut down, in reverse order. This is Dave's methodology from Artemis, preserved strictly in Sneeze. Dean considers this non-negotiable for architectural consistency and robust error handling.
- **Job-based compositor.** `AGENT::COMPOSITOR` is queue-driven via `POOL_CYCLE`, not self-paced. Each viewport gets a `JOB_COMPOSITOR` posted when `Activate()` is called. The pool routes `kSTATE_CREATE` and `kSTATE_DESTROY` exclusively to agent 0 (Filament thread affinity), while `kSTATE_RENDER` and `kSTATE_PRESENT` are available to any agent. When multiple viewports are active, the round-robin scheduling (by `m_nLastFrame`) ensures fair frame distribution. `nHertz = 0` in the factory table (no metronome tick). Pool size = 1 agent (Filament requires all API calls on a single thread — see Filament threading constraint below). The old single-loop `DwmFlush()` pattern has been replaced — frame pacing is now implicit in the render/present cycle. `Cancel()` blocks the deactivating thread until the compositor thread completes destruction on agent 0.
- **Engine metronome signals only nHertz > 0 agents.** The engine thread iterates the agent list and only calls `Signal()` on agents whose `nHertz != 0`. This is the mechanism for skipping self-paced agents without hardcoding special conditions.
- **Input contract.** Artemis calls `pViewport->Input_Mouse()` and `pViewport->Input_Key()` each frame. These accumulate input state per viewport under `m_mxInput` (inside Impl). `AGENT::COMPOSITOR`'s `Execute_Render` calls `pViewport->Input_Consume()` to atomically read and reset the accumulated mouse deltas/scroll. Thread-safe, no data races.
- **Framebuffer handoff (fallback path).** When native surface rendering is NOT active, `Execute_Present` reads the framebuffer via `pRenderer->GetFrameBuffer()`, copies to the per-viewport shared buffer via `pViewport->FrameBuffer_Write()` under `m_mxFrameBuffer`. Artemis calls `pViewport->FrameBuffer_Capture()` (returns pointer + dimensions, locks mutex), presents via SDL, then `pViewport->FrameBuffer_Release()`. Classic producer-consumer with mutex. When native surface rendering IS active (Filament presents directly to the Vulkan swapchain), the entire publish block is skipped -- no `FrameBuffer_Write`, no `OnFrameReady`.
- **Frame-ready notification.** After writing the framebuffer (fallback path only), `Execute_Present` calls `pHost->OnFrameReady(puFB, nFbW, nFbH)` with the framebuffer captured via `FrameBuffer_Capture()`. Artemis implements `IVIEWPORT` as `VIEWPORT_HOST` and handles presentation however it sees fit. This decouples the engine from any assumption about how the application works -- no `PostMessage`, no `InvalidateRect`, no platform-specific signaling from the engine.
- **THREAD base class.** Threading primitives live in `THREAD` (`sneeze/Engine.h` / `sneeze/Thread.cpp`). `CONTROL` and `AGENT` inherit `THREAD`. Lifecycle: `Initialize()` spawns `Main()`, blocks until `Ready()`; `~THREAD()` calls `Signal(true)` and joins. **`Wait` policy (authoritative detail under Design Principles — THREAD / CONTROL / AGENT wait and shutdown contract):** the predicate overload is `m_cvThread.wait(lock, fnWork)` with **no** `m_bShutdown` / `IsShutdown()` inside `Thread.cpp`; the timed overload is `wait_for` only. `Signal(bool)` wakes waiters and optionally latches shutdown.
- **AGENT base class.** All agents inherit `AGENT` (which inherits `THREAD`). Constructor takes `(POOL* pPool, int nAgentIz)`, stored as `m_pPool` and `m_nAgentIz`. `Engine()` delegates to `m_pPool->Engine()` — no cached engine pointer. `Main()` is pure virtual. Signal-driven placeholders use `Wait([this]{ return Tick(); })`; scrub agent uses `Wait([this]{ return Job(); })` — predicate semantics live in `bool Tick()` / `bool Job()`, not duplicated in `Main()` lambdas (same Design Principles subsection). Compositor agents use `Wait([this] { return Job(); })` with `POOL_CYCLE::Grab()`. Static table `aAgent_Init` (`AGENT_INIT`). Scrub jobs are posted directly by `ENGINE::Impl::Scrub()` via `CONTROL::Queue_Post_Scrub()`.
- **Console window for Win32 debug output.** `AllocConsole()` + `freopen_s()` added to Artemis's `WinMain()` to create a console window for `fprintf(stdout)` visibility. All Sneeze diagnostic messages (module init status, body count, FPS) and error messages route through `fprintf(stdout/stderr)`. To be made a selectable option when the title bar menu is restored.
- **FPS logging.** Per-viewport `Diagnostics()` counts frames and accumulates per-section timing via `Accumulate()`; once per second prints `FPS: N (frame Xms | input Xms | scene Xms | submit Xms | render Xms | publish Xms)` via `Engine()->Log()`. "submit" = CPU scene prep (`BuildScene`/`UpdateScene` + `anariCommitParameters`), reported by renderer's `GetLastSubmitSeconds()`; "render" = GPU dispatch + vsync wait (`anariRenderFrame` + `anariFrameReady`), reported by renderer's `GetLastRenderSeconds()`. `Diagnostics()` is called by `Execute_Present` at the end of each frame. **Current findings (native surface rendering, scene retention):** 60 FPS, frame ~16.8ms. Input 0.0ms, scene 0.1ms, submit 0.0ms (down from 0.9ms before scene retention), render 16.5ms (vsync-dominated). The entire render time lives inside `anariRenderFrame` — `anariFrameReady` returns instantly (0.0ms). Filament's `beginFrame()` blocks on vsync (FIFO swapchain), does the GPU work, and returns all within `anariRenderFrame`. **Known:** `ANARI_WAIT` vs `ANARI_NO_WAIT` in `anariFrameReady` does not affect the render time — the block is upstream in Filament's `beginFrame()`, not in the ANARI frame-ready poll.

**Metronome:**
- `nInterval` renamed to `nHertz` — values are cycles per second, not a multiple of the base interrupt.
- Engine metronome uses **drift-free fixed-origin scheduling**: each `do`/`while` iteration runs `if (!IsShutdown()) {` computes `tpNow`, `dElapsed = now - tpOrigin`, and ticks all pools via `pPool->Tick(dElapsed)` (which internally advances per-agent `nLastTick` / `Signal()` when `floor(dElapsed * nHertz)` crosses thresholds); `}` `else break;` then `Wait(std::chrono::milliseconds(1))` on CONTROL's `THREAD` mutex/cv. Time is always measured from a fixed origin, never accumulated from deltas — eliminates drift.
- `timeBeginPeriod(1)` / `timeEndPeriod(1)` called at metronome start/exit (Windows) to guarantee 1ms sleep resolution. Links `winmm.lib`.
- Metronome logs measured signal counts per agent once per second: `METRONOME: [1] 1/1 Hz [2] 30/30 Hz ...`
- Test Hz values in the factory table: compositor=0 (self-paced), scrub=1, C=30, D=60, E=64. Agents F, G, H were removed (excess placeholders).
- **Empirical result**: all Hz targets achieved perfectly, including 144 Hz — confirmed even before `timeBeginPeriod` was added (Windows 11 appeared to already have 1ms resolution from another process). `timeBeginPeriod` was added anyway to not rely on luck.
- `AGENT` base class has wake-rate measurement infrastructure (`m_nWakeCount`, `m_nLastReportSec`, `m_nAgentIz`, `AgentIndex()`) — currently commented out in `Control()`. Can be re-enabled for diagnostics.

**Per-viewport timing diagnostics:**
- Five timed sections per frame, accumulated via `VIEWPORT::Accumulate()`: input/camera (`m_dAccumInput`), scene build (`m_dAccumScene`), ANARI submit (`m_dAccumSubmit` — from `GetLastSubmitSeconds()`), ANARI render (`m_dAccumRender` — from `GetLastRenderSeconds()`), framebuffer publish (`m_dAccumPublish`).
- Logged once per second as per-frame averages in milliseconds alongside FPS via `VIEWPORT::Diagnostics()`.
- `m_tpLastFrame` is set once in `Renderer_Initialize()` and updated at the end of each `Diagnostics()` call — measures frame-to-frame duration for FPS calculation.
- **Current findings (native surface rendering, scene retention)**: 60 FPS, frame ~16.8ms. Input 0.0ms, scene 0.1ms, submit 0.0ms, render 16.5ms, publish 0.0ms. Scene retention eliminated the 0.9ms submit overhead. The render time is entirely `anariRenderFrame` (Filament's `beginFrame()` vsync wait + GPU work); `anariFrameReady` returns in 0.0ms. A dispatch/wait timing split was attempted (measuring `anariRenderFrame` and `anariFrameReady` separately) but backed out because all time lives in dispatch, making the split uninformative — the vsync wait cannot be separated from GPU work at the ANARI abstraction level.
- **Hierarchical scene traversal with WORLD_FRAME.** `Execute_Render` calls `TraverseNode(pSomRoot, rootFrame, tmNow, aSpheres, aCurves)` with an initially-zeroed `WORLD_FRAME` struct. `WORLD_FRAME` accumulates world-space position, radius, color, and star-flag down the scene hierarchy. Three cases by celestial subtype: (1) **SYSTEM nodes** (STARSYSTEM/PLANETSYSTEM/MOONSYSTEM/DEBRISSYSTEM) call `Position(tmNow)` to compute orbital position, add it to `childFrame.dPosX/Y/Z` (meters→AU conversion), and if `HasOrbit()`, generate `CURVE_DATA` for orbit trail visualization. No sphere rendered. (2) **BODY nodes** (STAR/PLANET/MOON/DEBRIS) capture `Radius()` → `childFrame.dRadius`, `m_Properties.fColor` → `childFrame.fColor`, and star flag → `childFrame.bStar`. No sphere rendered — bodies are invisible coordinate frames that carry physical properties. (3) **SURFACE nodes** (SURFACE) emit `SPHERE_DATA` using the inherited `childFrame` from the parent body: position from accumulated `dPosX/Y/Z`, radius from `dRadius` (clamped to `MIN_SPHERE_RADIUS`, scaled by `SUN_RADIUS_SCALE` if star), color from `fColor`, emissive from `bStar`, and texture data from the surface node's own `MAP_OBJECT`. This design makes the compositor entirely oblivious to orbital mechanics, tilt, spin, and precession — it only sees the results through `Position()` and `Rotation()` virtual calls on `MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL`.

**Deferred:**
- Converting Artemis's main loop from `PeekMessage` to `GetMessage` (no longer needs to run asynchronously since Sneeze drives rendering).

**C++14 targeting:**
- Dean intends to target C++14 instead of C++17 for broader compatibility. An audit of C++17 dependencies is needed but deferred. Key concern areas: `std::optional` (used in `MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL` for optional physical properties like mass, GM, pole coordinates), `std::filesystem`, structured bindings. Third-party headers (jwt-cpp, nlohmann/json) that assume C++17 are isolated behind module boundaries. Core Sneeze code (`std::thread`, `std::mutex`, `std::chrono`, `std::function`) is C++11/14.

