### Dependency Depot (Implemented)

**Status:** Implemented and operational. There is no top-level `CMakeLists.txt` — deps and Sneeze are two fully independent CMake projects.

**Model.** Chromium's `depot_tools` / `third_party` separation, adapted for a single-repo layout. Two fully independent CMake trees, no top-level bridge; build scripts in `scripts/` are the sole glue.

**Canonical directory layout** (all under `Sneeze/`, all `deps/builds/` + `deps/repos/` + `builds/` are gitignored):

```
Sneeze/
├── deps/
│   ├── CMakeLists.txt                    Standalone deps project (cmake -S deps)
│   ├── <dep>.cmake                       One ExternalProject_Add per dep
│   ├── repos/                            Shared source clones, reused across cfgs
│   │   ├── ANARI-SDK/
│   │   ├── Halogen/
│   │   ├── filament/
│   │   ├── Vox/
│   │   └── ... (all other deps)
│   └── builds/<platform>/<config>/       e.g. windows-x64/{debug,release}/
│       ├── build/                        Outer deps SuperBuild scratch + EP stamps
│       │   ├── .dep-stamps/              Script-level per-dep .done markers
│       │   └── <dep>-prefix/             ExternalProject_Add's internal stamps
│       └── libs/
│           └── <Dep>/{build,install}/    Per-dep inner build + usable install
├── src/                                  Standalone Sneeze project (cmake -S src)
│   └── CMakeLists.txt
└── builds/<platform>/                    Sneeze's own output (single multi-config tree)
    ├── build/                            Sneeze CMake scratch — one tree, both configs
    └── install/<config>/                 Per-config install; mirrors libs/<Dep>/install/
        ├── lib/                          Sneeze.lib / libSneeze.a
        └── bin/                          Test executables + CLI tools
```

**Platform slugs:** `windows-x64`, `linux-x64`, `linux-arm64`, `macos-arm64`, `macos-x64`, `ios-arm64`, `android-arm64` — must match `Artemis/pkg/manifest.json`. **Config** folder names are lowercased (`debug`/`release`) even though `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE` is `Debug`/`Release`. **Single Sneeze build tree, two configs:** `builds/<platform>/build/` carries both Debug and Release; emission to `install/<config>/` is chosen per `cmake --build --config`. The deps side stays per-config because each dep is built by its own `ExternalProject_Add` invocation against a pinned `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE`.

**Build commands (recommended entry point — the `scripts/build-*` wrappers, which handle stamp bookkeeping and dep ordering):**

```powershell
# Windows (PowerShell)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1                              # Sneeze only, Release (default)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Config Debug                # Sneeze only, Debug
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Fresh                       # Reconfigure Sneeze (no build)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Deps                        # Deps only (Release)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Deps -Config Debug          # Deps only (Debug)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -All                         # Deps, then Sneeze
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only filament               # Build one dep if not cached (implies -Deps)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only filament -Rebuild      # Full-scrub rebuild of one dep
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Deps -Rebuild               # Full-scrub rebuild of all deps
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Rebuild                     # Full-scrub rebuild of SNEEZE ONLY (deps untouched)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -All -Rebuild                # Full-scrub rebuild of deps + Sneeze
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -List                        # Stamp cache state
```

```bash
# Linux / macOS (shell)
./scripts/build-linux.sh                                 # Sneeze only, Release (default)
./scripts/build-linux.sh --config Debug                  # Sneeze only, Debug
./scripts/build-linux.sh --fresh                         # Reconfigure Sneeze (no build)
./scripts/build-linux.sh --deps                          # Deps only
./scripts/build-linux.sh --all                           # Deps, then Sneeze
./scripts/build-linux.sh --only filament --rebuild       # full-scrub one dep
./scripts/build-linux.sh --deps --rebuild                # full-scrub all deps
./scripts/build-linux.sh --rebuild                       # full-scrub SNEEZE ONLY (deps untouched)
./scripts/build-linux.sh --all --rebuild                 # full-scrub deps + Sneeze
```

**Mode flags are mutually exclusive:** `-Deps`, `-All`, `-Fresh` — only one at a time. `-Only` and `-List` implicitly enable deps mode. `-Rebuild` is a **modifier, not a mode** — it composes with whichever target set the other flags pick, and on its own (no `-Deps`/`-Only`/`-All`) it operates on Sneeze alone and never touches `deps/`. Default (no flags) is Sneeze-only: plain `cmake --build builds/<plat>/build --config <cfg>` with no dep checks, no reconfigure. If the Sneeze build tree doesn't exist yet, the plain-build fails with "CMakeCache.txt missing" and the user must re-run with `-Fresh` (or `-All` if deps are also missing).

**Under the hood — direct CMake invocations (used by CI):**

```bash
# All deps (any platform)
cmake -S deps -B deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build \
   -DSNEEZE_CONFIG=<Debug|Release> \
   -DSNEEZE_PLATFORM=<plat> \
   -DSNEEZE_DEP_REPO=deps/repos \
   -DLIBS_DIR=deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs
cmake --build deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build --config <cfg>

# Single dep (CI parallelization)
cmake -S deps -B deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build -DDEP=<name> ...
cmake --build deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build --target <name> --config <cfg>

# Sneeze (single multi-config tree; pass the Multi-Config generator on Unix)
cmake -S src -B builds/<plat>/build \
   -G "Ninja Multi-Config" \                             # omit on Windows (VS is default)
   -DLIBS_DIR=deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs \
   -DSNEEZE_CONFIG=<Debug|Release> \                     # seeds find_package
   -DSNEEZE_PLATFORM=<plat> \
   -DSNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT=builds/<plat>
cmake --build builds/<plat>/build --config <cfg>
```

**Hard separation invariant.** `deps/CMakeLists.txt` never reads from or writes under `src/`, and `src/CMakeLists.txt` never reads from or writes under `deps/` (it only consumes the installed headers + libs via `${LIBS_DIR}/<Name>/install/` paths passed in on the cmake command line). Neither file includes the other. This is a hard requirement. The scripts are the only glue: they orchestrate deps build, then Sneeze configure + build, as two separate cmake invocations.

**Script-level stamp system.** `scripts/build-windows.ps1` (and the `scripts/build-deps.sh` bash counterpart) maintain per-dep `.done` marker files under `<DepsBuildDir>/.dep-stamps/`. Once a dep builds successfully, its stamp is written and subsequent runs skip it. Stamps are orthogonal to `ExternalProject_Add`'s own internal step stamps (download/update/patch/configure/build/install).

**`-Rebuild` / `--rebuild` — the full-scrub rebuild *modifier*.** The single, unambiguous "I don't care what state this was in, start over" escape hatch. Applies to whatever target set the other flags pick out. **Never crosses the src ↔ deps wall on its own.** Behavior matrix:

| Invocation | Deps touched? | Sneeze touched? | What happens |
|---|---|---|---|
| `-Rebuild` alone | no | yes | Wipe `builds/<plat>/` (shared `build/` + both configs' `install/`), reconfigure, build Sneeze |
| `-Rebuild -Only <dep>` | that one dep | no | Scrub script stamp + EP prefix + `libs/<dep>/`; rebuild it |
| `-Rebuild -Deps` | all deps | no | Wipe entire per-config dep root (`deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/`); rebuild every dep |
| `-Rebuild -All` | all deps | yes | Deps scrub + rebuild, then Sneeze scrub + rebuild |

Source clones in `deps/repos/<dep>/` are **always** preserved — filament alone takes 10+ min to re-clone, and local dev work on a clone should never be silently blown away. Deps-side scrub is implemented by the `Remove-DepState` helper (PowerShell) / `remove_dep_state` (bash); Sneeze-side scrub is a plain `Remove-Item`/`rm -rf` on `builds/<plat>/` (which wipes BOTH configs' install dirs, since the Sneeze tree is now a single multi-config tree).

`-Rebuild` is a pure modifier — it can only touch `deps/` when `-Deps`, `-Only`, or `-All` is explicitly on the command line. On its own, it operates exclusively on the Sneeze tree.

**`Invalidate-DepConfigure` helper.** Before invoking `cmake --build --target <dep>`, the scripts explicitly delete `<DepsBuildDir>/<dep>-prefix/src/<dep>-stamp/<Config>/<dep>-configure` — the ExternalProject configure-step stamp. This forces the inner configure to re-run on every invocation, so edits to `deps/<dep>.cmake` (changed CMAKE_ARGS, new BUILD_COMMAND, etc.) take effect without the developer having to manually delete build trees. Without this, a failed build whose configure previously succeeded would reuse the stale cached configure on retry.

**Configuration isolation (deps).** Debug and Release live in fully separate **deps** trees — `deps/builds/<plat>/{debug,release}/`. No sharing of build outputs across configs. Every dep (including Filament + Halogen, post-PR-#15) tracks `SNEEZE_CONFIG`. The historical `LNK2038` mismatches between Halogen + Sneeze are now prevented by `deps/filament.cmake` disabling `FILAMENT_SHORTEN_MSVC_COMPILATION` on Debug and `deps/halogen.cmake` pinning `CMAKE_MSVC_RUNTIME_LIBRARY` per-config. See the "Halogen dependency chain" section above for details.

**Multi-config build (Sneeze standalone + Artemis consumer).** `src/CMakeLists.txt` carries a path generalization block that rewrites every dep path variable and every imported target (transitive across `anari::anari_static` + `vox::vox`) so they resolve at build time against `$<LOWER_CASE:$<CONFIG>>` instead of the single `SNEEZE_CONFIG` used at configure time. This lets **both** (a) Sneeze's standalone build at `builds/<plat>/build/` and (b) Artemis's consumer tree (via `add_subdirectory`) produce Debug and Release from a single CMake tree — one `.sln` on Windows (VS dropdown flips configs), Ninja Multi-Config on Linux/macOS, `cmake --build … --config <cfg>` to pick which config emits. `CMAKE_CONFIGURATION_TYPES` is pinned to `Debug;Release` *before* `project()` so VS/Xcode/Ninja-MC don't probe `MinSizeRel` / `RelWithDebInfo` paths that don't exist under `deps/builds/<plat>/`. The rewriter has a `_sneeze_resolve_variant` helper that probes disk for Debug-suffix filename variants (`libcurl-d.lib`, `openxr_loaderd.lib`, `spirv-cross-cored.lib`) because simple `/release/` ↔ `/debug/` substitution doesn't handle those name changes. Active whenever `USE_LOCAL_DEPS` is on (the default for both standalone and consumer). Output dirs (`CMAKE_{ARCHIVE,LIBRARY,RUNTIME}_OUTPUT_DIRECTORY` and their `_DEBUG` / `_RELEASE` variants) all point into `${SNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT}/install/$<LOWER_CASE:$<CONFIG>>/{lib,bin}`, keeping the two configs in sibling install trees under a shared build root.

**Source clones are shared.** `deps/repos/<Name>/` is a single git checkout per dep, reused across Debug and Release builds. Saves disk and clone time.

**Caveats:**
- To force a single dep to re-clone: delete `deps/repos/<name>/` (usually unnecessary — set `GIT_TAG` and let ExternalProject handle it).
- To force a single dep to fully rebuild: `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only <name> -Rebuild -Config <cfg>` (scrubs the script stamp, the ExternalProject prefix, and the per-dep `libs/<name>/` build + install trees; next invoke re-downloads/patches/configures/builds/installs top-to-bottom).
- Stale CMake caches in inner dep build dirs can silently resolve to wrong paths (see the `find_package` caveat in Known Gotchas). Nuking `deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs/<Name>/build/` is the escape hatch.

**Developer workflow:**
- **First build:** run `-All` once per config — deps (~35-90 min) then Sneeze (~1-2 min). Day-to-day work never touches the deps phase.
- **Day-to-day:** plain `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1` (seconds). No CMake, no dep checks, just compile + link Sneeze.
- **After editing CMakeLists.txt:** `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Fresh` to reconfigure Sneeze only (does NOT build). Follow with a plain `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1` to build, or use `-Fresh -Rebuild` to combine reconfigure + clean + build.
- **What `-Fresh` actually does (precisely):** passes `cmake --fresh` (3.24+), which wipes `CMakeCache.txt` + the `CMakeFiles/` directory before rerunning configure. It does **not** build or delete compiled `.obj` / `.lib` / `.dll` outputs. Scope is always Sneeze-only; the dependency libs under `deps/builds/` are never touched by `-Fresh`. For a true from-zero rebuild of everything: `-All -Rebuild` in one shot (scrubs + rebuilds deps then scrubs + rebuilds Sneeze).
- **After pulling a new dep version:** `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only <name> -Rebuild` forces that one dep to rebuild from scratch while every other dep stays cached.

**Recommended daily workflow on Windows — use Visual Studio, not the scripts.** Once `-All` has produced a configured Sneeze tree, the CMake machinery has already generated a full `.sln` at `builds\windows-x64\build\Sneeze.sln` (single file, multi-config). For day-to-day "I edited a `.cpp`, rebuild" work, open the solution in Visual Studio and use F7 — incremental builds are faster than re-invoking the scripts, and you get the debugger, breakpoints, IntelliSense, Error List, and the rest of the IDE for free. The Debug ↔ Release dropdown in the toolbar flips configs without reopening; outputs land in `install\debug\{bin,lib}` or `install\release\{bin,lib}` accordingly. The scripts exist for the cases Visual Studio can't solve: CI, Linux/macOS builds, fresh-checkout smoke tests, and reconfigure after editing `CMakeLists.txt` (which is what `-Fresh` is for). The rule of thumb: **fresh-checkout / config-changes / cross-platform → scripts; daily editing → `.sln` in VS.** Same deal on macOS with the Xcode project CMake produces, and on Linux with Ninja Multi-Config + your editor of choice. CMake's command-line UX is legitimately rough; nobody should have to live in it day-to-day.

## Naming Rationale — CONTROL, AGENT, SILO

ENGINE has three subordinate classes: **CONTROL**, **NETWORK**, and **STORAGE**. The names are deliberately symmetric — short, noun-form, parallel structure.

**CONTROL** (`sneeze/control/`) owns the engine thread, pool vector, metronome, and job queues. **POOL** is the non-template base managing agents and Hz-driven tick. **POOL_QUEUE<JOB_PTR>** adds typed job queues. **AGENT** is the abstract base class for engine threads (COMPOSITOR, SCRUB, FETCH, C). The CONTROL/AGENT pairing echoes the TV show "Get Smart" — an intentional pop-culture nod that also happens to be the right name. CONTROL is symmetric with NETWORK and STORAGE; AGENT accurately describes what the threads are (autonomous units acting on behalf of the engine).

**SILO** (peer in `SNEEZE` namespace, un-nested from STORAGE) groups four `UNIT`s for a single container. "Silo" captures the isolation semantics — storage silos are departmentally isolated from each other within the browser, with no crossover between containers. `NETWORK::ASSET` is a different concept (a cached URL resource, not an isolated data store) and is unchanged.

## MBE Runtime Pipeline — Remaining Work

The following items were discussed during the MBE architecture sessions but are not yet implemented or not yet wired up. The building blocks (classes, methods, data structures) exist for most of these — what's missing is the integration code that connects them.

### Wiring and Orchestration

1. ~~**Fabric instantiation orchestration**~~ — **DONE.** Full end-to-end pipeline operational. CONTAINER creates a WASM_STORE on `Open()` with linker initialized (32 host functions). `Fabric.cpp`'s `OnMsfReady` path enumerates modules from the parsed MSF, creates a `WASM_FETCH` per module (URL + SRI hash from the MSF payload), on successful fetch calls `CONTAINER::Instance_Open(twFabricIx, sUrl, sHash, aWasmBytes)` which compiles the WASM bytecode and instantiates it via linker. `Instance_Open` calls `CallInit()` and `CallOpen(twFabricIx)` after successful instantiation. **Full solar system verified working with `solar_system.wasm`** — WASM module creates 1,245 scene objects in a 3-level hierarchy (System→Body→Surface) via `Scene.Node_Root` and `Scene.Node_Open` host functions: star/planet/moon/debris systems (orbital frames with orbit data + precession), bodies (radius, tilt, color), and surfaces (texture URLs + spin). All objects rendered with textures, orbit trails, and correct hierarchical positioning at 60 FPS. `astro::InjectSolarSystem` is commented out — WASM module has fully replaced it. Symmetric teardown via `Instance_Close` in `~Impl`. **Test data:** `tests/data/solar-system.msf` is a signed MSF referencing `solar_system.wasm` at `https://cdn.rp1.com/test/solar_system.wasm` with SHA-256 hash verification. **WASM source:** `tests/wasm/solar_system/` — Rust project with Python code generator (`gen_solar_system.py`) that parses the JavaScript Solar System project (`E:\Dev\SolarSystem\`) and generates 10 `.rs` data files (star, planets, moons_{earth,mars,jupiter,saturn,uranus,neptune,pluto}, debris). Each file contains a `Submit()` function that builds and submits RMCOBJECT structs via host functions. Object indices are predefined (starting from 1, unique per object). **Performance note:** Jupiter's 79 moons and Saturn's 83 moons cause frame drops (1-2 FPS with all 1,245 objects); currently commented out in `lib.rs` to maintain 60 FPS. The performance bottleneck is in the renderer, not the WASM module or scene graph.

2. ~~**FABRIC -> WASM_STORE typed connection**~~ — **DONE.** CONTAINER owns `DEP::WASM_STORE*` (created in `Open()`, closed in `Close()`). FABRIC accesses the store through its CONTAINER (`pFabric->Container()->...`). The old `void* m_pOwner` in Fabric is no longer needed for this purpose.

3. **EVENT_SYSTEM not connected** -- The event system (Watch_Node, Watch_Tree, Fire_*) exists as a standalone class but: (a) there is no `EVENT_SYSTEM` instance in the engine, (b) `NODE::Node_Add`/`Node_Remove` don't call `Fire_NodeAdded`/`Fire_NodeRemoved`, (c) no code calls `Fire_NodeModified` on property writes. Needs an engine-owned instance and wiring into the SOM mutators.

4. **SPATIAL_INDEX not connected** — `SPATIAL_INDEX` exists but nothing collects SOM nodes into a flat list and calls `Build()`, and nothing calls `QueryFrustum`/`QuerySphere`. Needs integration into the compositor (frustum culling) and potentially a host function for proximity queries.

5. **THREAD_POOL not connected** — `THREAD_POOL` exists but is not instantiated by `WASM_RUNTIME` or `ENGINE`. No work is submitted to it. Needs initialization during engine startup and work dispatch from WASM store execution paths.

6. ~~**Host function linker registration**~~ — **DONE.** `WASM_STORE::InitializeLinker()` creates a `wasmtime_linker_t` and registers all 32 host functions (Console 14, Storage 6, Scene 10, Timer 2) via `RegisterFunc()`. Host functions receive `WASM_STORE*` as `pEnv`, bridge to CONTEXT via `GetHostData()`.

7. **Host function implementations** — **Partial.** Scene host functions `Scene_Node_Root` and `Scene_Node_Open` are fully implemented — they read RMCOBJECT from WASM linear memory (via wasmtime memory export), construct MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL instances from the wire format (including all RMCOBJECT substruct fields: type, orbit, transform, bound, properties, resource/texture URL), create NODEs in the SOM via `CONTAINER::Node_Root`/`Node_Open`, and return `twObjectIx` handles to WASM. `Node_Open` uses the RMCOBJECT `Head.Parent.ObjectIx()` to find the parent node in the container's handle table and calls `pParent->Node_Add(pChild)`. Texture loading is automatic — if `RMCOBJECT::Resource.sReference` is non-empty, `Node::Initialize()` triggers an async fetch via NETWORK. `Scene_Node_Close` implemented. Remaining Scene functions (Position, Scale, Bound, Color, Name, Radius, Texture) are stubbed — currently unused since the WASM module sets all data at creation time via the RMCOBJECT wire format. Console host functions use `ENGINE::Log()` as a temporary placeholder (correct routing through STREAM pending). Storage and Timer host functions are stubbed. `ReadWasmString()` utility for reading strings from WASM linear memory is implemented. Each remaining implementation needs access control checks (via `AccessControl.h`).

### Features Not Yet Started

8. ~~**Cache -> HTTP integration**~~ — **Done.** MANAGER::FetchEntry() uses libcurl directly to stream downloads to disk on background threads. HTTP status checked (2xx only), redirects followed, 300s timeout.

9. ~~**Module hash validation**~~ — **Done.** SRI-format hashes (sha256/sha384/sha512) parsed and verified via BoringSSL EVP_Digest. Hash mismatch -> FAILED, file deleted. Persistent entries verified on fetch; unhashed entries can be upgraded.

10. **AgentAnimator** — Discussed as a dedicated 64Hz animator thread that traverses the SOM and interpolates animation state on map objects. `AGENT::B` was repurposed as `AGENT::SCRUB` (disk cleanup). The animator role will be assigned to a different placeholder agent (`AGENT::E` at 64Hz is a natural fit). Needs: rename, SOM traversal, animation data model on MAP_OBJECT, interpolation logic.

11. **WASM CPU budgeting (fuel metering)** — Wasmtime fuel metering is proven in WasmTest but not wired into store creation. Each store should have a configurable fuel budget.

12. **WASM memory caps** — Per-store linear memory limits. Not implemented.

13. **Overlay fabrics** — The root fabric structure supports overlay siblings alongside the primary fabric, but no overlay nodes are created or managed.

### Teardown Gaps

14. **Teardown phase 2 (Communicate)** — Currently a log line. Needs to actually await async acknowledgements from active WASM instances before proceeding to phase 3.

15. **Teardown instance lifecycle** — `DestroyAllStores` deletes stores (destructor deletes instances), but it doesn't call `CallClose`/`CallShutdown` on active instances before destruction. The proper sequence is: CallClose on all open fabrics per instance, then CallShutdown on each active instance, then destroy the store.

